# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-cake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apple-cake/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apple-cake/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apple-cake/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apple-cake/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apple-cake/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apple-cake/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apple-cake/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:apple-cake/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:apple-cake/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:apple-cake/amandine-dessert] These cakes are among the most traditional "sweetshop" cakes in Romania.
[src:apple-cake/amandine-dessert] The original recipe has layers of chocolate sponge cake soaked in rum flavored caramel syrup.
[src:apple-cake/amandine-dessert] The cream filling is a combination of chocolate buttercream mixed with fondant.
[src:apple-cake/amandine-dessert] The assembled layers are glazed with a combination of fondant with chocolate and rum or rum essence, poured over the cake while still slightly liquid.
[src:apple-cake/amandine-dessert] These cakes also have a traditional decoration on top with a little bit of the cream and a diamond-shaped piece of thin chocolate.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] Apples are also used in other cakes to add moisture and sweetness, often as a partial substitute for refined sugar.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] Regions of Great Britain and Ireland have the ideal climate for apple growing, making apple cake a common dessert with many regional varieties throughout.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] However, it is in the traditionally agricultural West Country of England that apple cakes have been raised as culinary symbols of their counties, such as Dorset apple cake, Devonshire apple cake, and Somerset apple cake.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] A recipe for Dorset apple cake was first recorded in the Bridport News on 27 November 1896, and has since been voted as Dorset national dish.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] Cider cakes originate from the South West and Herefordshire, with various versions incorporating the alcoholic apple based beverage either in the cake batter or steeping the fruit inside the cake.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] The Irish apple cake is different from their English counterparts, in that slices of apple are sandwich within the sponge mixture.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] The Welsh apple cake, *Tiesen Faa* and can be eaten as with a cup of tea or as a dessert with custard or cream, while the Welsh Harvest cake resembles the Irish apple cake but has the addition of sultanas and cinnamon.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] On Guernsey, they have a suet based apple cake called Gâche Melée.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] Apple is a common fruit in German baking.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] The *Versunkener Apfelkuchen* (sunken apple cake) is an apple cake that has apples halves, usually peeled and hasselbacked, sunk into the sponge cake batter.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] *Apfelkuchen mit Hefeteig* (apple cake with yeast dough) combines apples with a rich yeast dough, like a traditional coffee cake.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] *Apfelstreuselkuchen* (apple streusel cake) is a sheet cake with apples and streusel over the top.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] An *Unsichtbarer Apfelkuchen* (invisible apple cake) pairs a large volume of thinly sliced apples with just enough thin batter to retain the shape of the cake after baking.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] An apple cake in Poland is called *jabłecznik*, made from a sponge or yeast-based dough with a spiced apple filling.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] It can be topped with *kruszonka* (crumbles), meringue, or a dusting of caster (powdered) sugar.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] An additional layer of budyń (a Polish variation of custard) can sometimes be found.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] In restaurants and cafes, it is usually served hot with whipped cream and coffee.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] In Scandinavia, apple cakes are typically prepared from sour apples and baked in a dough made from sugar, butter, flour, eggs, and baking powder.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] The cake is then topped with apples, cinnamon and sugar, sometimes also chopped almonds.
[src:apple-cake/apple-cake] In Sweden and Norway it is usually served tepid with whipped cream, custard (vanilla sauce) or vanilla ice cream.
